</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="19E7BEF9FF3CCEECFAB3FC72DEF83F90" box="[1356,1451,931,958]" captionStart="FIGURE 159" captionStartId="176.[136,235,1273,1297]" captionTargetBox="[187,1358,189,1237]" captionTargetId="figure-264@176.[151,1436,186,1249]" captionTargetPageId="176" captionText="FIGURE 159. Actinopus pindapoy sp. nov., male: A–C ZMB 19824: A. Copulatory bulb, prolateral; B. Copulatory bulb, dorsal; C. Copulatory bulb, retrolateral. PA-Paraembolic apophysis; BTA-Basal Tegular Apophysis; PAc-Prolateral Accessory keel; PI- Prolateral Inferior keel; PS-Prolateral Superior keel. Scale line: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5597577" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5597577/files/figure.png" pageId="177" pageNumber="178">Fig. 159</figureCitation>
A–C) by the wider bulb and from those of 
<taxonomicName id="46DCD9FFFF3CCEECFAFEFC19DE333FCC" authorityName="Rios-Tamayo &amp; Goloboff" authorityYear="2018" box="[1281,1376,968,994]" class="Arachnida" family="Actinopodidae" genus="Actinopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="177" pageNumber="178" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ariasi">
<emphasis id="B3A87E6EFF3CCEECFAFEFC19DE333FCC" box="[1281,1376,968,994]" italics="true" pageId="177" pageNumber="178">A. ariasi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the presence of a conspicuous serrated area on embolar base and, according to 
<bibRefCitation id="E54DDF8DFF3CCEECFC0CFBC3DE3A3802" author="Rios-Tamayo, D. &amp; Goloboff, P. A." box="[1011,1385,1042,1068]" pageId="177" pageNumber="178" pagination="1 - 83" refId="ref140496" refString="Rios-Tamayo, D. &amp; Goloboff, P. A. (2018) Taxonomic revision and morphology of the trapdoor spider genus Actinopus (Mygalomorphae: Actinopodidae) in Argentina. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 419, 1 - 83. https: // doi. org / 10.1206 / 0003 - 0090 - 419.1.1" type="journal article" year="2018">Ríos-Tamayo &amp; Goloboff (2018)</bibRefCitation>
, from those of 
<taxonomicName id="46DCD9FFFF3CCEECFC6CFBE6DF6F387F" authorityName="Rios-Tamayo &amp; Goloboff" authorityYear="2018" box="[915,1084,1079,1105]" class="Arachnida" family="Actinopodidae" genus="Actinopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="177" pageNumber="178" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cordobensis">
<emphasis id="B3A87E6EFF3CCEECFC6CFBE6DF6F387F" box="[915,1084,1079,1105]" italics="true" pageId="177" pageNumber="178">A. cordobensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the legs with metatarsi and tarsi similarly colored (
<bibRefCitation id="E54DDF8DFF3FCEEFFE6CFF4FD8553C96" author="Rios-Tamayo, D. &amp; Goloboff, P. A." box="[403,774,158,184]" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" pagination="1 - 83" refId="ref140496" refString="Rios-Tamayo, D. &amp; Goloboff, P. A. (2018) Taxonomic revision and morphology of the trapdoor spider genus Actinopus (Mygalomorphae: Actinopodidae) in Argentina. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 419, 1 - 83. https: // doi. org / 10.1206 / 0003 - 0090 - 419.1.1" type="journal article" year="2018">Ríos-Tamayo &amp; Goloboff, 2018</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 15 B). According to 
<bibRefCitation id="E54DDF8DFF3FCEEFFE6BFF13D8563CF3" author="Rios-Tamayo, D. &amp; Goloboff, P. A." box="[404,773,194,221]" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" pagination="1 - 83" refId="ref140496" refString="Rios-Tamayo, D. &amp; Goloboff, P. A. (2018) Taxonomic revision and morphology of the trapdoor spider genus Actinopus (Mygalomorphae: Actinopodidae) in Argentina. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 419, 1 - 83. https: // doi. org / 10.1206 / 0003 - 0090 - 419.1.1" type="journal article" year="2018">Ríos-Tamayo &amp; Goloboff (2018)</bibRefCitation>
, females of 
<taxonomicName id="46DCD9FFFF3FCEEFFEF9FF36DA3B3D2F" authorityName="Rios-Tamayo &amp; Goloboff" authorityYear="2018" box="[262,360,231,257]" class="Arachnida" family="Actinopodidae" genus="Actinopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="coylei">
<emphasis id="B3A87E6EFF3FCEEFFEF9FF36DA3B3D2F" box="[262,360,231,257]" italics="true" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">A. coylei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished by the shape of their spermathecae with a squared base and a long external lobe, slightly straight or curved inward (
<bibRefCitation id="E54DDF8DFF3FCEEFFDACFEFEDA643D43" author="Rios-Tamayo, D. &amp; Goloboff, P. A." pageId="178" pageNumber="179" pagination="1 - 83" refId="ref140496" refString="Rios-Tamayo, D. &amp; Goloboff, P. A. (2018) Taxonomic revision and morphology of the trapdoor spider genus Actinopus (Mygalomorphae: Actinopodidae) in Argentina. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 419, 1 - 83. https: // doi. org / 10.1206 / 0003 - 0090 - 419.1.1" type="journal article" year="2018">Ríos-Tamayo &amp; Goloboff, 2018</bibRefCitation>
, fig 17 D–E).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
